Sometimes I feel ashamed to be a European.
Last year more than a million people in need of our help arrived in Europe and our response was downright pathetic.
There are so many contradictions.
We mourn the tragic death of two-year-old Alan Kurdi, yet more than 200 children have since drowned in the Mediterranean.
International treaties recognize that refugees are a collective responsibility, yet we accept that little Lebanon hosts more Syrians than all of Europe combined.
We lament the existence of smugglers, yet we make them the only viable route to seek asylum in Europe.
We lack manpower, yet we prevent people corresponding to our economic and demographic needs from coming to Europe.
We proclaim our liberal values in opposition to fundamentalist Islam, yet -- we have policies of repression that arrest underage asylum seekers, separate children from their families and seize refugee property.
What do we do ?
How did we come to this, that we adopted such an inhumane response to a humanitarian crisis?
I don&#39;t think it&#39;s due to a lack of interest, at least I don&#39;t want to believe it.
I think it&#39;s because our politicians don&#39;t have a vision, they don&#39;t know how to adapt the international asylum rules, created more than 50 years ago, to globalization.
I want to step back and ask two fundamental questions, the two questions we all need to ask.
First, why is the current system not working?
Second, how can we fix it?
The current refugee regime was created as a result of the aftermath of World War II by these people.
Its primary purpose is to ensure that when a state fails, or worse, turns against its people, people have a place to go, to live in safety and with dignity until they can return.
It was created precisely for situations such as the current situation in Syria.
Through an international convention signed by 147 governments, the 1951 Convention relating to the Status of Refugees, and an international organization, the UNHCR, States have agreed to reciprocally admit to their territory people fleeing conflict and persecution.
But today, this system is failing.
In theory, refugees have the right to seek asylum.
In practice, our immigration policies block the path to safety.
In theory, refugees have the right to integration or return to their country of origin.
But in practice, they remain stuck in eternal limbo.
In theory, refugees are a common global responsibility.
In practice, geography means that countries close to the conflict host the overwhelming majority of refugees.
The system isn&#39;t broken because the rules are bad
but because we don&#39;t apply them adequately to a changing world, and that&#39;s what we need to reconsider.
I will explain to you how the current system works.
How does the current refugee regime work?
But not from an institutional perspective, more from a refugee&#39;s point of view.
Imagine a Syrian woman. Let&#39;s call her Amira.
For me, Amira represents
many people I met in the area.
Amira, like 25% of refugees in the world, is a woman with children, and she cannot return home because she comes from this city that you see: Homs. A city that was once beautiful and historic and is now in ruins.
Amira cannot go back there.
But Amira has no hope of settling in a third country, because there is a lottery available to only less than 1% of refugees.
Amira and her family face an impossible choice.
They have three options.
The first option is for Amira to take her family to a camp.
In the camp, she could be helped, but there is little future for Amira and her family.
The camps are in austere and arid places, often in the desert.
In the Zaatari camp in Jordan, at night you hear the shelling from across the border.
Economic activity is restricted.
Education is often of poor quality.
Around the world, around 80% of refugees who are in camps must stay there for at least 5 years.
It&#39;s a miserable life, and that&#39;s probably the reason why, in reality, only 9% of Syrians choose this option.
An alternative for Amira is to head to the urban area of a neighboring country, such as Amman or Beirut.
This is an option chosen by around 75% of Syrian refugees.
But it also has challenges.
Refugees in such urban areas often do not have the right to work.
They often don&#39;t have access to help.
And so when Amira and her family have spent all their savings, they will have nothing left and will be in urban misery.
There is a third possibility that an increasing number of Syrians are choosing.
Amira can seek hope for her family by risking their lives on a dangerous and perilous journey to another country, and that is what we see today in Europe.
We therefore offer refugees an almost impossible choice between three options: encampment, urban misery or a dangerous journey.
For refugees, that choice is today&#39;s refugee regime.
But I believe that is a false choice.
We can reconsider this choice.
The reason we limit these options is because we think they are the only options available to refugees, but that is not the case.
Politicians see this as a zero-sum problem, if we benefit refugees, citizens pay the price.
We tend to think of refugees as an inevitable cost or a burden on society.
But they don&#39;t have to be. They can contribute.
What I mean is that there are ways to increase opportunities and that everyone benefits: host countries and communities, our societies and refugees.
And I want to suggest four ways to transform our view of refugees.
These four perspectives have one thing in common: they embrace the opportunities of globalization, mobility and markets, and modernize the way we think about the refugee problem.
The first idea is that of enabling environments. It starts with the fundamental recognition that refugees are human beings like everyone else, but with extraordinary circumstances.
With my colleagues from Oxford, we embarked on a research project in Uganda, observing the economic life of refugees.
We chose Uganda not because it is representative of all host countries.
He is exceptional.
Unlike the majority of host countries, Uganda has provided an economic opportunity for refugees.
It gives them the right to work, the freedom to move.
And the results are extraordinary, for the refugees and for the host community.
In the capital, Kampala, we found that 21% of refugees own a business employing people and 40% of these employees are natives of the host country.
In other words, refugees create jobs for citizens of the host country.
Even in the camps, we have discovered extraordinary examples of dynamic and thriving businesses.
For example, in a village called Nakivale, we have the example of Congolese refugees running digital music sharing businesses.
We found a Rwandan who runs a business to enable young people to play video games on recycled consoles and televisions.
Despite the hardships of extreme constraints, the refugees are innovating and the man you see is a Congolese named Demou-Kay.
Demou-Kay arrived in the camp with very few possessions, but he wanted to become a director.
So, with friends and colleagues, he started a community radio station, he rented a camera and made films.
He&#39;s made two documentaries with and for our team and he&#39;s building a successful business out of next to nothing.
These are the kinds of examples that should guide our response to refugees.
Rather than seeing refugees as inevitably dependent on humanitarian aid, we must provide them with the opportunity for human development.
Yes, clothes, blankets, shelter, food are very important in the emergency phase, but we need to go further.
We must provide the opportunity of connectivity, electricity, education, the right to work, access to banks.
Everything that we take for granted, that integrates us into the global economy can and should be offered to refugees.
The second idea I want to talk about is economic zones.
Unfortunately, not all host countries in the world have Uganda&#39;s approach.
Most host countries do not open their economies to refugees in this way.
But there are always pragmatic options we can use.
Last April, I went to Jordan with my colleague, the development economist, Paul Collier, and we thought about an idea that we had there with the international community and the government, an idea to create jobs for Syrians while supporting Jordan&#39;s national development strategy.
It is the idea of an economic zone where we could potentially integrate the employment of refugees as well as the employment of natives of the host country.
15 minutes from the Zaatari camp, which hosts 83,000 refugees, is the King Hussein Bin Talal Development Zone.
The government spent more than $100 million to connect it to the electricity grid and the road network, but two things were missing: access to labor and foreign investment.
so that refugees can work there rather than being stuck in camps, support their families, develop skills through vocational training before returning to Syria.
We recognized that Jordan would benefit from this, as its development strategy required moving from a middle-income country to an industrial country.
The refugees would benefit from it but it would also contribute to the reconstruction of Syria after the war, recognizing that we must incubate the refugees because they are the best resource to rebuild Syria.
We published this idea in the journal Foreign Affairs.
King Abdullah picked up the idea.
This was announced at the London conference on Syria and a test will start during the summer.
The third idea I want to put to you is the notion of preference between states and refugees leading to positive outcomes that you see in this selfie featuring Angela Merkel and a Syrian refugee.
We rarely ask refugees what they want, where they want to go, but we can do it and it will be better for everyone.
Economist Alvin Roth developed the idea of matching markets, where the order of preference of the parties determines their eventual match.
My colleagues Will Jones and Alex Teytelboym have looked at ways to apply this idea to refugees, asking refugees to rank destinations but also allowing states to rank the kind of refugees they want based on skills or languages, and then to match them.
Of course, quotas should be put in place for diversity and vulnerability, but it is a way to increase the chances of a match.
The idea of matching is successfully used for, for example, distributing college students, matching kidney donors and patients, and the algorithm exists on dating sites.
Why not apply this to offer choice to refugees?
It could also be used at the national level where one of the biggest challenges is persuading local communities to accept refugees.
Currently, in my country, for example, we often send engineers to rural areas and farmers to cities, which makes no sense.
Matching markets bring together these preferences and listen to the needs and demands of the host population and refugees.
The fourth idea I want to talk about is the humanitarian visa principle.
The tragedies and disorders seen in Europe could have been avoided.
They stem from a fundamental contradiction in European asylum policy: in order to seek asylum in Europe, you must arrive spontaneously by embarking on a dangerous journey that I have already spoken about.
But why are these trips necessary in the era of low-cost airlines and modern consular means?
These trips are not necessary and last year they led to the death of more than 3,000 people at Europe&#39;s borders and within Europe.
If refugees had the right to travel directly and seek asylum in Europe, we would avoid this. And we can do that through humanitarian visas which allow people to get a visa from an embassy or consulate in a neighboring country and then pay for their ferry or plane ride to Europe.
It costs around €1,000 to pay a courier from Turkey to the Greek islands.
A low-cost flight from Bodrum to Frankfurt costs €200.
If we allowed refugees, that would have major benefits.
It would save lives, reduce the market for smugglers and mark an end to the disorder seen on the European frontline in areas like the Greek islands.
It is the laws that prevent us from doing so, not a rational solution.
It is an idea that has been applied.
Brazil took a forward-thinking approach and more than 2,000 Syrians obtained humanitarian visas, traveled to Brazil and, upon arrival, applied for refugee status.
In this configuration, every Syrian who did this received refugee status and was recognized as a refugee.
There is a historical precedent.
Between 1922 and 1942, these Nansen passports were used as travel documents allowing 450,000 Assyrians, Turks and Chechens to travel to Europe and claim refugee status elsewhere in Europe.
And Nansen&#39;s International Refugee Office received the Nobel Peace Prize in recognition of this viable strategy.
Each of these four ideas that I presented to you are ways to expand Amira&#39;s choices.
These are ways that we have to increase the choice of refugees beyond these options, these three impossible options that I have detailed for you, while benefiting others.
In conclusion, we need a new perspective, a vision that expands the choice of refugees but recognizes that they don&#39;t have to be a burden.
There is nothing inevitable about refugees being a cost.
Yes, they are a humanitarian responsibility, but they are human beings with skills, talents, aspirations and the ability to contribute, if we allow them.
In the new world, migration will not stop.
What we have seen in Europe will continue for years.
People will travel again, populations will be displaced and we have to find rational and realistic ways to manage it, not based on the old logics of humanitarian aid, charity, but building on the opportunities offered by globalization, markets and mobility.
I urge you to wake up and I urge our politicians to wake up to this challenge.
Thank you so much.
When I was little, I dreamed of the ocean.
A wild place, very colorful and full of life, home to bizarre and fantastic creatures.
I imagined big sharks reigning supreme and graceful sea turtles twirling through the corals.
First a marine biologist, then a photographer, I spent most of my career looking for places as magical as the ones I dreamed of as a child.
As you can see, I started exploring water very early.
But the first time I really went underwater was when I was about 10 years old.
I vividly remember giving determined strokes to reach this old cannon embedded in a shallow coral reef.
When I was finally able to catch it, I looked up and found myself surrounded by fish in every color of the rainbow.
That day, I fell in love with the ocean.
Thomas Peschak Marine Conservation Photographer In 40 years on Earth, I&#39;ve had the great privilege of exploring some of the craziest seascapes for National Geographic and the Save Our Seas Foundation.
I&#39;ve photographed everything from huge sharks to tiny ones that fit in the palm of your hand.
I smelled the fish on the breath of humpback whales feeding beside me in cold Canadian waters near the Great Bear Rainforest.
I even knew all about green turtle love rituals in the Mozambique Channel.
We all leave a footprint on the ocean and vice versa.
And the pristine seas that I dreamed of as a child are always harder to find.
They are always smaller and more threatened.
As we humans maintain our role as the planet&#39;s greatest predator, I have witnessed and photographed first-hand repercussions.
For a long time, I thought I had to shock my audience with disturbing images to get them out of their indifference.
This approach has its merits, but I came back from it.
In my opinion, the best way to produce change is to sell love.
If you will, I am a couple maker and as a photographer I have the unique opportunity to reveal animals and entire ecosystems lying beneath the surface of the ocean.
You can&#39;t love and fight for something if you don&#39;t know it exists.
Revealing this - that&#39;s the power of marine photography.
Among the hundreds of underwater places I have seen, a handful of these landscapes have touched me deeply.
I saw the first of these landscapes about 10 years ago off the wild and rugged coast of South Africa.
Every summer, huge schools of sardines move north, a mass migration phenomenon called the Sardine Run.
A mad dash of these fish
where hordes of hungry and agile predators hunt them down.
Common dolphins hunt together and manage to isolate sardines from the main school and create small schools.
They dive and trap fish up against the surface and swoop in to enjoy their wriggling feast.
The sharks follow closely.
For many people, sharks and dolphins are sworn enemies, but during the Sardine Run, they live side by side.
In fact, dolphins help sharks feed more efficiently.
Without the dolphins, the small shoals created are more sparse and the sharks often end up with a &quot;sardine doughnut&quot; or a mouthful of water.
I had a few spirited moments with the sharks on the Sardine Run, but I know they don&#39;t see me as prey.
I received blows and was jostled like all the other participants in this brawling banquet.
Let&#39;s leave the African coast to go east, across the immensity of the Indian Ocean to the Maldives, an archipelago of coral islands.
During the monsoon season, manta rays from all over the archipelago travel to a tiny islet in Baa Atoll called Hanifaru.
Armies of crustaceans, most smaller than a marble, are the staple food of manta rays.
When plankton concentrations are low, manta rays feed on their own and they flip backwards, in a loop, like a puppy chasing its tail.
When the density of plankton increases, the rays line up in single file and form these long chains. Every delicious bite that escapes the first is gobbled up by the second or the next.
When the concentration of plankton reaches its peak, the manta rays swim ever closer in a rotating movement by which they feed.
As they swirl through this tight formation, the column of manta rays creates its own vortex, sucking in and bringing plankton right into the rays&#39; cavernous mouths.
The experience of diving among these innumerable rays is absolutely unforgettable.
When I first photographed Hanifaru, the site was unprotected and threatened by development.
I&#39;ve worked with NGOs like Manta Trust, and my photos have helped make Hanifaru a marine protected area.
Fishermen from neighboring islands hunted these manta rays, they used their skin to make traditional drums.
Today, they are the staunchest conservationists and manta rays contribute more than $8 million to the Maldives economy each year.
I&#39;ve always wanted to go back in time and see an era where the maps were incomplete or said, &quot;Dragons here.&quot;
I got the closest to it by visiting these remote atolls in the heart of the Indian Ocean.
Far, far away from boat and fishing lines, diving in these waters is a poignant memory of what our oceans once looked like.
Bassas da India is largely unknown. It&#39;s a tiny wedge of coral in the Mozambique Channel.
Its barrier forms a shield that protects its inner lagoon, a nursery for Galapagos sharks.
These sharks are anything but shy, even during the day.
Something told me they would be even bolder and more numerous at night.
I found myself facing more sharks than ever, gathered on a single outcrop.
Photographing and sharing moments like these reminds me of why I chose this path.
Not long ago I was working on a project in Baja California for National Geographic.
Halfway down the Pacific coast is San Ignacio Lagoon, where the gray whale comes to give birth.
For a century, this coast was the scene of a systematic massacre, more than 20,000 gray whales were killed there, leaving only a few hundred to survive.
Today, the descendants of these same whales play on the surface with their offspring and they even interact with us.
This species has done remarkably well.
On the other side of the peninsula is Cabo Pulmo, a sleepy fishing village.
Decades of overfishing have brought them to the brink of collapse.
In 1995, local fishermen convinced the authorities to make their waters a marine reserve.
But what happened next was a miracle.
In 2005, after only a decade of protection, scientists recorded the greatest increase in fish.
But don&#39;t take my word for it, come with me.
In one breath swim the depths with me amidst one of the largest and densest schools of fish I have ever encountered.
We all have the ability to inspire hope.
And through my photos, I would like to convey the message that it is not too late for our oceans.
And I would especially like to highlight the resilience of nature in the face of 7.3 billion people.
My hope is that in the future, I will have to search hard to make photos like this, while creating images that show our respectful coexistence with the ocean which,
I hope, will become everyday for me.
To thrive and survive doing my job, you really have to be an unfailing optimist.
I always work thinking that the next fabulous image that will serve my purpose is all ready, just behind the next reef, in the heart of the next lagoon, or who knows, maybe in the one after that.
When I moved to Harare in 1985, social justice was at the heart of Zimbabwe&#39;s national health policy.
The new government was emerging from a long war of independence and immediately announced a socialist program: health services, primary education became essentially free.
A major expansion of rural health centers has placed approximately 80% of the population within two hours&#39; walk of one, a truly remarkable achievement.
In 1980, the year of independence, 25% of children in Zimbabwe were fully immunized.
In 1990, a decade later, this proportion was 80%.
I felt extremely privileged to be part of this transformation, a revolution.
The excitement, the camaraderie was palpable.
Working with brilliant Zimbabweans — scientists, doctors, activists — I felt connected not just to an African independence movement, but to a progressive global movement for public health.
But there were considerable challenges.
Zimbabwe reported its first case of AIDS in 1985, the year I arrived.
I had cared for a few AIDS patients in the early 1980s during my medical training at Harlem Hospital, but — we had no idea what was in store for Africa.
My first few days there, the infection rate was 2%.
This would skyrocket to one in four adults by the time I left Harare 17 years later.
By the mid-1990s, I had told hundreds of middle-aged people that they had HIV.
I had seen friends and colleagues, my students, patients in the hospital die.
In response to this, my colleagues and I set up a clinic.
We were demonstrating the use of condoms.
We launched education in school, interventions in the workplace.
We were doing research. We gave advice to the partners of infected men so that they knew how to protect themselves.
We worked hard, and at the time I thought I was doing my best.
I provided excellent treatment, as good as I could get.
But I wasn&#39;t talking about structural change.
Former UN Secretary Kofi Annan spoke honestly about his personal failure that led to the Rwandan genocide.
In 1994, he was the director of the peace department at the UN.
At a memorial 10 years later, he said: &quot;At the time I thought I was doing my best, but I realized after the genocide that I could and should have done more to sound the alarm and gather support. »
The AIDS epidemic took the health community by surprise, and today, when the World Health Organization estimates that 39 million people have died from this disease, I am not alone in feeling remorse and regrets for not having done more, sooner.
But when I was living in Zimbabwe, I didn&#39;t see my role as that of an advocate or a politician.
I was there because of my technical skills, my clinical skills and my epidemiological research.
For me, my job was to care for patients and do research to better understand transmission patterns within the population, and I hoped that we would slow the spread of the virus.
I was aware that marginal populations had a very high risk of having and dying of AIDS.
And on the sugar plantations, which up close looked more like feudal strongholds than any modern business, 60% of pregnant women had HIV.
I worked to show that being infected was not a moral failure but rather linked to a culture of male superiority, forced immigrant labor and colonialism.
The whites were largely spared.
As health professionals, our tools were pitifully weak: imploring people to change their individual behavior, to use condoms, to reduce the number of partners.
Infection rates were climbing. And when a treatment was available in the West, which remained our strongest weapon against the virus, it was not affordable to the African public sector.
I did not denounce the unequal access to these life-saving drugs or the underlying economic and political systems that were driving up infection rates in large sections of the population.
I rationalized my silence by telling myself that I was only a visitor to this country, that sounding the alarm could get me deported, prevent me from doing my job, taking care of my patients, do much needed research.
So I didn&#39;t rebel against the government&#39;s initial position on AIDS.
I didn&#39;t voice my concerns out loud.
Many doctors and health professionals may think that I did nothing wrong.
Our pact with our patients, the Hippocratic oath and its variants, evokes the inviolability of the patient-doctor relationship.
I did everything I could for every patient I had.
But I knew that epidemics appear along the cracks in our society, reflecting not only our biology, but most notably patterns of marginalization, exclusion, discriminations linked to race, gender, sexuality, class, etc
It was true for AIDS.
This was true recently for Ebola.
Medical anthropologists like Paul Farmer, who has worked on AIDS in Haiti, have called this &quot;structural violence.&quot; Structural because inequalities are embedded in the political and economic organization of our social world, and are often invisible to the eyes of the privileged and those in power; and violence because its impact—untimely death, suffering, disease—is violent.
We do little for our patients if we do not recognize these social injustices.
Sounding the alarm is the first step towards good public health practice, and it&#39;s how we can rally support to revolutionize and create change together.
Today, I am not silent.
I talk about many things, even if they make those who listen to them uncomfortable, even if they make me uncomfortable.
A lot of what I say has to do with racial differences and institutionalized racism, things that are no longer supposed to exist in this country, let alone in medical practice or public health.
But they exist and we pay for them by shortening lives.
That is why sounding the alarm about the health impact of racism in the United States, the current institutional and interpersonal violence faced by people of color, entwined with our sad legacy of 250 years of slavery, 90 years of Jim Crow and 60 years of imperfect equality, sounding the alarm about this is fundamental to the successful completion of my job as New York City Health Commissioner.
In New York, premature mortality — dying before reaching age 65 — is 50% higher for black men than for whites.
In 2012, a black woman was 10 times more likely than a white woman to die in childbirth.
Although we have made tremendous strides in reducing infant mortality rates, a black baby is still almost three times more likely than a white baby to die in its first year.
New York is no exception.
These statistics are compared with statistics made across the United States.
A recent analysis by the New York Times reported that there were, in the country,
1.5 million black men missing. They spoke of the fact that more than one in six black men who would be between the ages of 25 and 54 today no longer led a normal life, but were in prison or died prematurely.
There is great injustice in the daily and disproportionate violence against young black men, the focus of recent #BlackLivesMatter protests.
But we must remember that persistent disparate rates and the occurrence and outcome of common diseases—heart disease, cancers, diabetes, HIV—diseases that can kill softly and silently and take away even more black lives prematurely.
When the #BlackLivesMatter movement took shape, I was frustrated and angry that the medical community was reluctant to use the word “racism” in our research and work.
You must have felt something every time I said it.
Our students have participated in protests in white coats, but the medical community has largely stood aside as current discrimination continues to affect disease patterns and mortality.
And I fear that the fashion for personalized and precise medicine, the search for biological or genetic targets for a more suitable treatment, could inadvertently cause us to lose sight of the big picture, that is to say the daily context, where a person lives, grows, works, loves, fundamental factor in determining the health of the population: for too many of us, poor health.
As healthcare professionals, in our daily work, whether in practice or in research, we witness a great injustice: homeless people who are unable to follow medical advice because they have other priorities; transgender youth thinking about suicide because our society is too rigid; the single mother who is made to feel responsible for her child&#39;s ill health.
Our role as healthcare professionals is not just to treat our patients but to sound the alarm and promote change.
Whether it&#39;s legal or not, our position in society makes us very credible and we shouldn&#39;t spoil that.
I regret that I did not speak in Zimbabwe, and I have promised myself that as New York City Commissioner of Health, I will use every opportunity I have to sound the alarm and support for health equity.
I will speak out against racism, and I hope you will join me, and I will join you in speaking out against sexism or any other form of inequality.
