You probably don&#39;t know Kenema in Sierra Leone, or Arua in Nigeria.
For me these are the two most extraordinary places on Earth.
There, in the hospitals, there is a community of nurses, doctors and scientists who have calmly fought one of humanity&#39;s deadliest threats in years: the Lassa virus.
The Lassa virus resembles the Ebola virus.
It can cause high fever and can often be fatal.
But these people risk their lives every day, to protect individuals in their communities, and ultimately to protect us all.
One of the most amazing things I learned about them during one of my first visits a long time ago was that they start every morning – those tough mornings on the frontlines – with singing.
They come together, and they show their joy and their strength.
Over the years, we have visited each other. I could be among them, sing, and write. It was extraordinary, because it reminds us that we are not here only for science, but that we are linked by a shared humanity.
You can imagine it was extremely important, vital even, when things started to change.
The situation changed in March 2014, when the Ebola epidemic was declared in Guinea.
It was the first outbreak in West Africa, near the border of Sierra Leone and Liberia.
It was scary... We were all terrified.
We had suspected for some time that Lassa and Ebola were more widespread than previously thought, that it could reach Kenema.
So members of my team immediately joined Dr. Humarr Khan and his team in the field. We have set up diagnostics to perform molecular tests capable of detecting the arrival of Ebola in Sierra Leone.
We had already succeeded in controlling the Lassa virus. We knew how to do it, the team was remarkable.
We just had to give them the tools and the lab for Ebola.
Unfortunately, that day has come.
On May 23, 2014, a woman arrived in the hospital&#39;s maternity ward. The team carried out the molecular tests and identified the first case of the Ebola virus in Sierra Leone.
It was an exceptional job.
They were able to diagnose the case immediately, treat the patient safely, and begin to understand what was going on.
It could have prevented what happened.
But the day it happened, the epidemic had been brewing for several months.
There were already hundreds of cases, surpassing all previous outbreaks.
She entered Sierra Leone, not like this singular case, but like a tidal wave.
We worked with the international community, the Ministry of Health, with Kenema, to deal with the cases. The following week there were 31, then 92, then 147 cases, they were all coming to Kenema, one of the only places in Sierra Leone that could solve this problem.
We worked tirelessly, trying everything we could to help each person, and trying to get attention. We also did something else:
we didn&#39;t throw away the blood tests, used to detect Ebola, we put them in a chemical to deactivate them. We packed them up and shipped them across the ocean.
We sent them to Boston, where my team works.
We have also worked tirelessly, day after day. We quickly generated 99 Ebola virus genomes.
The genome is the blueprint for a virus.
We all have one.
It tells us what we are made of, and gives us so much information about us.
The results of this kind of work are simple and very useful.
We took these 99 different viruses, we looked at them and compared them, and we found that, comparing them to the three genomes that had been previously published in Guinea, the epidemic had emerged in Guinea several months earlier, and that, once in humans, it was transmitted from human to human.
This is very important when determining how to intervene, because contact tracing is essential.
The virus has also been found to mutate as it moves between humans.
Each mutation is important because diagnostics, vaccines, and our therapies are all based on the sequence of the genome. It is the guide.
Global health experts need to respond, develop and re-calibrate all their work accordingly.
But science doesn&#39;t work that way. My position at the time was that I had the data and I could have worked in silos for months, analyzed the data carefully, slowly, submitted a paper for publication, made some edits, and finally published my data after publication. official.
This is how the status quo in science works.
This time, no question of doing so.
We had friends in the field. For us, it was obvious that we needed the help, a lot of help...
The first thing we did, as soon as the machine released the first sequences, was to publish them on the web.
We published them and appealed for help.
